paragraph.docTitle:
Taxanes and taxoids of the genus
Taxus
– A comprehensive inventory of chemical diversity

paragraph.emphasis: Institute of Biological Chemistry and M.J. Murdock Metabolomics Laboratory, Washington State University, Pullman, WA, 99164-7411, USA

subSection.paragraph: ARTICLE INFO
Taxane
Taxoid

taxonomicName.authorityName: Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire & Cuvier

subSection.paragraph: ABSTRACT

The pseudoalkaloid diterpene Taxol® (paclitaxel) emerged as a best-selling anti-cancer drug in the mid-1990s. The compound attracted considerable interest because of its unique mechanism to stabilize microtubules, thus reducing dynamicity and ultimately promoting mitotic arrest. Taxol was originally isolated from members of the genus
Taxus
. Over the last 50 years, close to 600 metabolites with taxane scaffolds were isolated from various
Taxus species
and their structures reported. The present review article provides an overview of the known chemical diversity of taxanes, with an emphasis on the functionalization of diterpene scaffolds. The implications of the occurrence of chemically diverse taxane metabolites for unraveling Taxol biosynthesis and enabling pathway engineering are discussed as well.

The yew family ( Taxaceae ) consists of evergreen trees and shrubs that can be divided into six genera, which include
Amentotaxus
(4 species occurring mostly in China ),
Austrotaxus
(1 species found exclusively in New Caledonia , an island territory in the South Pacific),
Cephalotaxus
(6 species endemic to eastern Asia),
Pseudotaxus
(1 species occurring in southern China ),
Taxus
(number of species still a matter of debate; distribution across the northern hemisphere but mainly in North America, Europe and Southeast Asia), and
Torreya
(6 or 7 species native to East Asia and North America). The taxonomy of the genus
Taxus
has remained controversial, mostly due to the lack of diagnostic morphological characters and the high degree of similarity among species. For example, the Himalayan yew (
T. wallichiana Zucc.
) appears to have been referred to as
T. baccata
L. in some studies; similarly,
T. chinensis Rehd.
,
T. yunnanensis Cheng et L. K. Fu
and
T. mairei (Lemee and Lev.) Hu ex Liu
may have been used interchangeably by some authors ( Cope, 1998 ; Dempsey and Hook, 2000 ; Collins et al., 2003 ; Spjut, 2007 ; Coughlan et al., 2020 ). In the present work, we are not attempting to reevaluate such assignments and the taxonomic details given here are thus the same as those reported in the original papers. Yews are relatively slow growing but can reach substantial height ( 20 m ) and trunk circumference ( 5 m ), according to the United States National Register of Champion Trees (www.americanforests.org) ( Fig. 1A ).
Taxus
is thought to have descended from Paleotaxus rediviva , an extinct species preserved in

subSection.paragraph:
The term taxane is used for a large and diverse class of metabolites originally isolated from members of the genus
Taxus
(yews). Taxoids are derivatives of Taxol and are therefore a smaller group within the taxane class, but the term is sometimes used synonymously with ‘taxanes’. Structures of taxanes can be classified as belonging to one of eleven types based on the arrangement of their fused ring systems. Normal 6/8/ 6 taxanes have a linear tricyclic ring system (with the numbers indicating the size of each ring) ( Table 1 ). Other tricyclic ring systems are found in 11(15 → 1) abeo taxanes (5/7/6), 11(15 → 1),(10 → 9)di abeo taxanes (5/6/6), and 2(3 → 20)abeotaxanes (6/10/6). Tetracyclic ring systems are characteristic for 3,11-cyclotaxanes (6/5/5/6) and 14,20-cyclotaxanes (6/8/6/6). 3,11:12,20-Dicyclotaxanes (6/5/5/5/6) and 3,11:4,12-dicyclotaxanes (6/5/5/4/6) have pentacyclic skeletons. A hexacyclic ring system is found in 3,11:4,12:14,20-tricyclotaxanes (5/ 5/4/6/6/6). Bicyclic ring systems are representative of 3,8-secotaxanes (6/12) and 11,12-secotaxanes (8/6) ( Table 1 ). Cyclotaxane subclasses other than 3,1-cyclotaxanes each have less than a handful of known members, but they do have unique ring systems and are thus listed separately here. In the following paragraphs, we will detail the known chemical diversity for the above-mentioned taxane classes. Consistent with prior reviews on the topic ( Appendino, 1995 ; Baloglu and Kingston, 1999 ; Parmar et al., 1999 ; Wang et al., 2011 ), we have adopted a unified nomenclature for taxanes that may differ from the trivial names given in the original papers.

heading.emphasis: 3. Group I: Taxanes with a 6/8/6 ring system

subSection.paragraph:
Metabolites with a 6/8/6 ring system (nomenclature based on number of carbons in the A, B and C rings) ( Table 1 ) constitute the most common class of taxanes, with 349 known structures occurring in the genus
Taxus
. They are biosynthetically derived directly from taxa-4 (20),11-diene and often referred to as normal taxanes. They can be further subdivided based on the functionalization of the taxane core, as detailed below.

subSection.paragraph: The C-5 side chain is generally non-functionalized at C-2 ′ , apart from four metabolites that are hydroxylated ( Ando et al., 1997 ; Prasain et al., 2001 ; Shi et al., 2000c , 2004b ). The functional group on C-3 ′ carries two methyl groups in three-fourth of basic taxadienes (tertiary amines); in six cases a secondary amine with one methyl group is present in this position ( Shi et al., 1999c , d, 2003b, 2004b; Ishiyama et al., 2007 ); and one metabolite (7β,9α,10β,13α- tetraacetoxy-5α-[3’-(N-formyl-Nmethylamino)-3 ′ -phenyl-propanoyl-oxy]taxa-4(20),11-diene) possesses a tertiary amine with a methyl and a formyl group as substituents ( Zhang et al., 2008a ). subSection.paragraph:
A
C-13(17) oxido bridge
is present in three known 6/8/6-taxanes , which differ by their functionalization at C-5, which can be a hydroxyl, trans -cinnamoyl or 3 ′ - N,N -dimethylamino-3 ′ -phenylpropanoyl group ( Wang et al., 1997 ; Shigemori et al., 1999 ; Morita et al
., 2005 ) (
Table 10
).

Group I. 10.:
The eight members of the
taxa-4( 20),12-dienes
(double bond isomers of the more common taxa-4(20),11-dienes) share common functionalization at C-1 (none), C-2 (O-acetyl), C-9 (O-acetyl), and C-13 (O-acetyl) ( Table 11 ). Acetylation is also prevalent at C-7, with only one known exception (7-deacetoxytaxuspine D) (
Shi et al., 2003 b
).
C-10 is also mostly acetylated, with two metabolites carrying a hydroxyl group at that position ( Shigemori et al., 1999 ; Shi et al., 2003b ). The most varied functionalization is found at C-5: three known metabolites bear a trans -cinnamoyl moiety ( Kobayashi et al., 1995b ; Shigemori et al., 1999 ; Shi et al., 2003b ), two taxanes are hydroxylated at this position ( Zamir et al., 1999a ; Shi et al., 2005a ), Taxuspine P has a 3 ′ -N, N-dimethylphenyl-3 ′ -propanoyl group ( Kobayashi et al., 1996 ), one metabolite carries a 2 ′ -hydroxy-3 ′ -N,N-dimethylamino-3 ′ -phenylpropanoyl moiety ( Zhang et al., 2008b ), and one metabolite bears a 3’-(N-formyl-N-methyl-amino)-3 ′ -phenylpropanoyl residue ( Zhang et al., 2013 ). One metabolite (2α,7β,9α,10β, 13-pentaacetoxy-5α-(2 ′ -hydroxy-3 ′ -N,N-dimethylamino-3 ′ -phenylpropanoyloxy)taxa-4(20),12-dien-11β- ol) is hydroxylated at C-11, which is rare among 6/8/6-taxanes ( Table 11 )
.

subSection.paragraph:
Group I. 12.:
The structures of nine miscellaneous metabolites with a 6/8/8-taxane ring system , which did not fit neatly into any of the subclasses discussed above, are shown in Table 13
. Taxezopidine B possesses an unusual C- 3 ( 4 ) double bond ( Wang et al., 1998 ). An uncommon C-5(6) double bond is present in 2α,10β,13α- triacetoxytaxa-4 (20),5,11-trien-9-ol (
Shi et al., 2003 a
). Tetrahydrofuran ring moieties were identified in taxuyunnanine Z and Taxuspine K (at C-2(20)) as well as taxiwallinine (at C-10(16)) ( Wang et al., 1996b ; Li et al., 2003 ; Lun et al., 2017 ). A unique α,β- unsaturated lactone moiety appears in taxchinin N ( Zhao et al., 2006 ). A 6/8/6-taxane with an unprecedented hemiacetal ring between C-13 and C-9 was identified by Zhang et al. (2008c) . A 6/8/6-taxane with oxetane ring and an extraordinary C-7–C-9 peroxide was isolated from T. canadensis ( Pan et al., 2011 ). Finally, baccataxinine possesses a rare dioxolane ring between C-1 and C-2 ( Lei et al., 2018 ) Table 13.

Metabolites with a 5/7/
6 ring system (11(15→1) abeo taxanes) are an abundant class of taxanes, with 127 known structures reported for members of the genus Taxus ( Table 1 ). The first taxane of this class was observed in experiments where Taxol was treated with electrophilic reagents, which led to a mixture of products with opened oxetane ring and contracted A and B rings ( Samaranayake et al., 1991 ). It was later shown that such ring-contracted abeo taxanes are naturally occurring metabolites in Taxus species ( Appendino et al
., 1993 b). The following paragraphs summarize the known chemical diversity in the context of functionalization patterns of the 11 ( 15 →1) abeo taxane core.

heading.emphasis:
11. Taxane structural diversity in the context of
Taxus
taxonomy

subSection.paragraph:
The enormous chemical diversity of taxanes found in the genus
Taxus
begs the question if there are patterns for the occurrence of taxane classes across species. Before reporting on the results of a chemotaxonomic analysis, we need to briefly outline some of the challenges. Traditionally, the genus
Taxus
has included eight species based on their geographic distribution ( Cope, 1998 ): (1)
T. baccata
L. - Europe, North Africa and Southwest Asia, (2)
T. cuspidata Siebold & Zucc.
- East Asia , (3)
T. wallichiana Zucc.
– Himalayan range, (4)
T. sumatrana (Miq.) de Laub.
- southern China , Philippines , Taiwan , Sunda Islands of Indonesia , (5)
T. globosa Schltdl.
– Central America and Mexico , (6)
T. brevifolia Nutt.
– Pacific Northwest of the United States , (7)
T. floridana Nutt. ex Chapm.
- West Florida , and (8)
T. canadensis Marshall
– central and eastern North America. Based on detailed morphological characters, the genus was later proposed to include 24 species and 55 varieties ( Spjut, 2007 ). However, morphological studies suffer from a relatively high level of phenotypic plasticity even within a species. A further complication results from the fact that hybridization among species has been confirmed (for example,
T. cuspidata
x
T. canadensis
= T. x hunnewelliana and
T. baccata
x
T. cuspidata
= T. x
media
) ( Collins et al., 2003 ). Molecular phylogenetic analyses have not been entirely conclusive, but there appears to be an emerging consensus for the recognition of somewhere between nine and eleven species (
T. baccata , T. brevifolia , T. canadensis , T. chinensis
(to be included in
T. wallichiana
according to some authors),
T. cuspidata , T. floridana , T. fauna , T. globosa , T. mairei
(to be included in
T. wallichiana
according to some authors),
T. sumatrana and T. wallichiana
) ( Chaw et al., 1993 ; Li et al., 2001 ; Ge et al., 2008 ; Coughlan et al., 2020 ). There has clearly been confusion in reporting taxane constituents, with the Himalayan yew being referred to as
T. baccata
ssp. wallichiana ,
T. wallichiana
,
T. fuana
, and
T. contorta
; likewise, the Chinese yew has been referred to as
T. yunnanensis
,
T. mairei
,
T. chinensis
,
T. wallichiana
, and
T. sumatrana ( Hao et al., 2015 )
. It is impossible to resolve potential issues resulting from inconsistent species naming in the body of literature on taxanes, which spans more than five decades, and we thus must rely on the designation used in the original publication.

subSection.paragraph:
Keeping these limitations in mind, we can ask about the general occurrence of the major classes of taxanes across the genus
Taxus
(please note that we only consider species in which at least 25 taxanes have been reported, which eliminates
T. brevifolia
, T. globosa
and T. x
media
from further analysis). 6/8/6-Taxanes and 11(15 → 1) abeo taxanes were detected in all species that have been investigated ( Fig. 3A ). 2(3 → 20) Abeo taxanes were reported to occur in all but three species (not yet reported to be present in
T. brevifolia , T. chinensis
or
T. wallichiana
). Secotaxanes were characterized from
T. canadensis , T. chinensis , T. cuspidata , T. mairei ,
and
T. sumatrana
( Fig. 3A ). Cyclotaxanes were found in samples obtained from
T. baccata , T. canadensis , T. cuspidata
, and
T. yunnanensis
, while diabeotaxanes were isolated from only three species (
T. sumatrana , T. wallichiana
, and
T. yunnanensis
). Taxane classes with a small number of members have generally been reported to occur in fewer species. We believe this to be due to a sampling bias. For example, all known di abeo taxanes were isolated and characterized by three academic groups that focused on
Taxus species
commonly found in Asia. Similarly, the entire body of literature on taxanes from
T. sumatrana
was generated by Ya-Ching Shen’ s team, and the emphasis on these studies was on finding novel structures, not on reporting known ones. The low concentrations of some taxane classes could be another reason for the fact that they have not been detected in a larger number of
Taxus species.
While quantitative information on low abundance taxanes is scarce, the amount of starting material might allow for a rough estimatation: for example, Giovanni Appendino and his team processed 500 kg of
T. baccata
for the characterization of the first cyclotaxane ( Appendino et al. (1992c) , likely indicating a low abundance.

Questions could also be asked about functionalization patterns within a taxane class, which is only meaningful for 6/8/6-taxanes, a class representing roughly 350 different structures (only

Too few reports have been published on the occurrence of members of some 6/8/6-taxane subclasses (opened oxetane ring, oxido bridge, taxa-4(20),12- dienes, taxanes with a C-4(5)-double bond). However, 6/8/6-taxane subclasses with a larger number of members (C-5 side chain moieties, C-14 oxygenation, epoxide ring, oxetane ring or both an oxetane ring and a C-13 phenylisoserine side chain) occur in all
Taxus species
( Fig. 3B ).

In summary, we did not find convincing evidence for species-specific patterns of taxane accumulation. The key limitation of such an analysis is, however, the lack of coverage of taxane classes across
Taxus species.
We recognize the challenge of more inclusive analyses, as metabolite patterns are determined not only by genetics (at the species level) but also by environmental conditions, and additional limitations exist for the detection of low abundance constituents in complex matrices ( Bundy et al., 2009 ). Addressing this issue can be considered a grand challenge for the field.

subSection.paragraph: Bernd Markus (“Mark”) Lange was trained as a chemist with
B.Sc. and M.Sc. degrees from the University of Bonn in Ger-
many. He obtained his Ph.D. in 1995 from the University of
Munich. Following postdoctoral studies at the University of
Tübingen and Washington State University, Mark spent four
years in the biotechnology industry as a group leader for
Novartis, Syngenta and Diversa. In 2004, he transitioned back
into an academic position and rose through the ranks at
Washington State University, where he is currently a professor
at the Institute of Biological Chemistry and also directs the M.J.
Murdock Metabolomics Laboratory. Mark’ s academic research
program is focused on unraveling the biochemical pathways
leading to bioactive natural products, in particular those that
are synthesized and accumulated in specialized cell types such as glandular trichomes, resin ducts and laticifers.

Caleb Conner is a Graduate Research Associate at the Institute of Biological Chemistry at Washington State University. He received his master’ s degree from the University of North Texas Health Science Center in Medical Sciences , managed the R&D lab for a custom rubber mixer for two years, and is now working to attain his Ph.D. in Molecular Plant Sciences. He is currently investigating the chemistry and biochemistry of taxanes in the genus Taxus .
